❖ Check the intensity of negative controls using minfi :

This kind of probes usually should not hybridise and are used to measure the amount of background signal in the array, to assess technical variability, so it is important for assessing methylation levels in a correct way.

Getting the number of negative controls first (restricting our search to only probes of the type “Control”):

df_TypeControl <- data.frame(getProbeInfo(RGset, type = "Control"))

❖ Calculate detection pValues; for each sample, how many probes have a detection p-value higher than the threshold assigned to each student?

In this regard we will use detectionP() function, which provided by minfi and is used to detect the failed positions (i.e: the positions that report high background value compared to real signal and hence can be considered as noise to the real signal), using a p-value of 0.05 above which the p-value is considered insignificant and the positions should not be considered reliable.

First of all, creating a matrix of detection of pValues where the rows are the probes and the columns are the samples detectionP:

detP <- detectionP(RGset)
save(detP,file="detP.RData")
load("detP.RData")

Collecting all the failed probes in a logical matrix for all the probes, classifying the probes of them meeting the criteria of less than 0.05 threshold:

failed <- detP>0.05
table(failed)
## failed
##   FALSE    TRUE 
## 3881163    2933

The code above resulted in classifying the data into 3881163 pValues that are sufficient to trust the fluorescence values associated to the probes, and 2933 values that happen to have high pValues and should be discarded.

Classifying them on whether they should be trusted or not:

summary(failed)

As we see, the number of failed probes that is low considering the whole number of probes, additionally in an additiional next step, we can exclude any potential samples that had exceptionally and significantly higher number of failed positions according to a certain threshold, and another retaining method can be to exclude the probes that performed poorly in all the samples, using the functions colMeans() and rowMeans() respectively.

Getting the percentage of failed probes across samples:

means_of_columns <- colMeans(failed) 
samples_to_be_retained <- means_of_columns<0.05
RGset <- RGset[samples_to_be_retained]

From what was seen in means_of_columns, the percentage of failed probes is low in all the samples, all samples were retained.

Removing any possible probes that failed in a high number of samples(We can decide, for example, to retain only the probes in which <1 % of samples has a bad detection p-value (greater than 0.05, the threshold that we used to calculate the object failed)):

means_of_rows <- rowMeans(failed)
probes_to_be_retained <- means_of_rows<0.01 # I chose the threshold here as the one in class
table(probes_to_be_retained)
## probes_to_be_retained
##  FALSE   TRUE 
##   1397 484115

There are 1397 probes to be removed and 484115 to be retained.

Selecting the probes that we want to remove potentially and save them for any further potential steps:

probes_to_be_removed <- probes_to_be_retained[probes_to_be_retained==FALSE]
names_probes_to_be_removed <- names(probes_to_be_removed)

6- Calculate raw beta and M values and plot the densities of mean methylation values, dividing the samples in DS and WT (suggestion: subset the beta and M values matrixes in order to retain DS or WT subjects and apply the function mean to the 2 subsets).

First, the beta value represents the percentage of methylation at a given site (Beta=(M/(M+U))), a continous variable between 0 (absent methylation) and 1 (completely methylated), it is heteroscedastic.

While M value is a continous variable which can in principle take on any value on the real line(M=log2(M/U)), it is homoscedastic.

Getting the beta values using getBeta accessor function on MethylSet:

beta <- getBeta(MSet.raw)

Getting the beta values using getM accessor function on MethylSet class object as well:

M <- getM(MSet.raw)

Dividing the Beta and M values based being Wild Type or Down’s Syndrome:

beta_WT <- beta[,MSet.raw$Group=="WT"]
beta_DS <- beta[,MSet.raw$Group=="DS"]
M_WT <- M[,MSet.raw$Group=="WT"]
M_DS <- M[,MSet.raw$Group=="DS"]

Now, there are NA values that have the beta and M methylation/unmethylation values are equal to zero. and is undefined, we need to filter them out. Since we want to plot the density distribution now, we need to calculate the mean as well as getting rid of NA’s, we can use the function apply() :

mean_of_beta_WT <- apply(beta_WT,1,mean,na.rm=T)
mean_of_beta_DS <- apply(beta_DS,1,mean,na.rm=T)
mean_of_M_WT <- apply(M_WT,1,mean,na.rm=T)
mean_of_M_DS <- apply(M_DS,1,mean,na.rm=T)

Now we can have the density distribution:

d_mean_of_WT_beta <- density(mean_of_beta_WT)
d_mean_of_DS_beta <- density(mean_of_beta_DS)
d_mean_of_WT_m <- density(mean_of_M_WT)
d_mean_of_DS_m <- density(mean_of_M_DS)

Plotting the density distributions:

par(mfrow=c(2,1))

We can see from the observed results that there is a shift towards the left in samples with DS, which means that there are decreased methylation levels with samples with Down’s Syndrome, which might be of clinical importance as an observation.

❖ In both top graphs, we see that we have a great difference between probe types, the peak of type I is higher at low methylation levels and the peak of type II is higher at high methylation level, mainly because of the differences of the regions that these two different types are meant to analyse, because as we may know, type II is generally used for sites distant from CpG sites while type I forms a slight majority in CGI sites only (still present in shores and distant regions but not in sizeable amounts). Usually, density of beta values from type II is shifted towards the center and so it is not suitable for detection of extreme methylation values, solution is that by applying the correction, we can have the same profiles with the same peaks, so rescaling in topright graph in which the peak has moved to the right.

❖ In the middle two graphs, we can see that when the peak has become sharper and longer and the standard deviation has been reduced, they are both slightly shifted to lower values as well.

❖ In the bottom two graphs, we can see the data has been somehow centered, the interquartile range has increased as well and the variation decreased, data has been normalised to ensure that the distributions on each of the arrays are somehow identical.

9- Using the matrix of normalized beta values generated in step 7, identify differentially methylated probes between group DS and group WT using the function assigned to each student. Note; it can take several minutes; if you encounter any problem you can run the differential methylation analysis only on a subset of probes (for example those on chromosome 1, 18 and 21)

❖ Our aim is to identify the CpG probes that are differentially methyled between samples belonging to groups “DS” and “WT”. We will use a parametric test (t-test). Which performs one and two sample t-tests on vectors of data. we calculate the pvalue and if it is lower than our confidence threshold, the alternative hypothesis can be accepted and the null hypothesis to be rejected. We will use the t-test to compare the first CpG of beta_preprocessNoob between groups DS and WT:

t_test <- t.test(preprocessNoob_results_beta[1,] ~ SampleSheet$Group)

❖ We will use the apply() function to calculate the mean of each row of the matrix. However, unlike the mean() function, t.test() functions does not return a value, but a list; therefore, we have to create an ad hoc function:

My_ttest_function <- function(x) {
   t_test <- t.test(x~ SampleSheet$Group)
   return(t_test$p.value)
}
pValues_ttest <- apply(preprocessNoob_results_beta,1, My_ttest_function)

10- Apply multiple test correction and set a significant threshold of 0.05. How many probes do you identify as differentially methylated considering nominal pValues? How many after Bonferroni correction? How many after BH correction?

❖ We need to use Bonferroni for managing Family Wise Error Rate and Benjamin & Hochberg (BH) for False Discovery Rate, using the function p.adjust to adjust p-values in order to maintain the desired level of significance of the identified probe:

First of all, we will create a vector storing the p-values:

raw_pValues <- ttest_pvalues_and_beta$pValues_ttest

corrected <- data.frame(ttest_pvalues_and_beta, raw_pValues_BH, raw_pValues_bonferroni)

11- Produce a volcano plot and a Manhattan plot of the results of differential methylation analysis.

I- Volcano plot:

A volcano plot is constructed by plotting the negative log of the p value on the y axis (usually base 10). This results in data points with low p values (highly significant) appearing toward the top of the plot. The x axis is the log of the fold change between the two conditions. The plot also has areas to represent hyper and hypomethylation regions of the plot, usually on the topright (hyper) and topleft (hypo).

First, the difference between the average of group “WT” and “DS” values should be calculated. And to do that, we will have to create two matrices containing the beta-values of each group samples, and then we will calculate the mean within each group for each row, creating a dataframe with two columns, one containing the delta values and the other with the -log10 of p-values:

corrected_WT <- corrected[,1:8][,SampleSheet$Group=="WT"]
corrected_DS <- corrected[,1:8][,SampleSheet$Group=="DS"]

corrected_WT_mean_beta <- apply(corrected_WT,1,mean)
corrected_DS_mean_beta <- apply(corrected_DS,1,mean)

corrected_diff_mean <- corrected_WT_mean_beta - corrected_DS_mean_beta

toVolcPlot <- data.frame(corrected_diff_mean, -log10(corrected$pValues_ttest))
plot(toVolcPlot[,1], toVolcPlot[,2],pch=16,cex=0.5,xlab="difference in mean DNA methylation", ylab="-log10(P-value)")
abline(h=-log10(0.05),col="red")
toHighlight <- toVolcPlot[abs(toVolcPlot[,1])>0.1 & toVolcPlot[,2]>(-log10(0.05)),]
points(toHighlight[,1], toHighlight[,2],pch=16,cex=0.7,col="red")

12- Produce an heatmap of the top 100 differentially mehtylated probes.

A heatmap is used as a graphical representation of data where the individual values contained in a matrix are represented as colors. It is a false color image (basically image(t(x))) with a dendrogram added to the left side and/or to the top. Typically, reordering of the rows and columns according to some set of values (row or column means) within the restrictions imposed by the dendrogram is carried out.

As an heatmap on several thousands of probes is computationally demanding, for our analysis we will use just the top 100 most significant CpG probes. We will extract only beta values for these top 100 probes and convert them in a matrix.

We will use the function heatmap.2() to visualize the heatmap, itt wants a matrix as an input:

Complete linkage:

library(gplots) # the library needed to do a heatmap

heatmap.2(input_heatmap,col=terrain.colors(100),Rowv=T,Colv=T,dendrogram="both",key=T,ColSideColors=colorbar,density.info="none",trace="none",scale="none",symm=F,main="Complete linkage")

Single linkage:

heatmap.2(input_heatmap,col=terrain.colors(100),Rowv=T,Colv=T,hclustfun = function(x) hclust(x,method = 'single'),dendrogram="both",key=T,ColSideColors=colorbar,density.info="none",trace="none",scale="none",symm=F,main="Single linkage")

Average linkage:

heatmap.2(input_heatmap,col=terrain.colors(100),Rowv=T,Colv=T,hclustfun = function(x) hclust(x,method = 'average'),dendrogram="both",key=T,ColSideColors=colorbar,density.info="none",trace="none",scale="none",symm=F,main="Average linkage")

The figures affirm the difference between complete/average linkage approaches which perform better because the single linkage one suffers from long branches as what is evident. Yet still the average linkage approach is considered better among the two.
